<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<title>Patta Barawari Family Home - Architect Brief</title>
<style>
:root {
  --green:#173a2b;
  --green-soft:#6f816f;
  --brown:#7b4d27;
  --gold:#b58b56;
  --cream:#f7f0e6;
  --paper:#fffaf2;
  --ink:#1f261f;
  --muted:#70685e;
  --line:#ddcfbc;
}
* { box-sizing:border-box; }
body { margin:0; background:var(--cream); color:var(--ink); font-family:Georgia,"Times New Roman",serif; line-height:1.45; }
.page { width:1180px; min-height:760px; margin:28px auto; padding:32px; background:var(--paper); border:1px solid var(--line); box-shadow:0 8px 22px rgba(0,0,0,.10); page-break-after:always; }
h1 { margin:0; font-size:56px; line-height:1.02; color:var(--green); letter-spacing:-1px; }
.subtitle { margin:10px 0 20px; font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:1.6px; color:var(--brown); text-transform:uppercase; }
h2 { margin:0 0 22px; background:var(--green); color:white; padding:14px 18px; font:700 24px Arial,sans-serif; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.4px; }
h3 { color:var(--brown); font-size:23px; margin:0 0 10px; }
p { margin:0 0 12px; }
li { margin:5px 0; }
.grid2 { display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:24px; }
.grid3 { display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr); gap:18px; }
.grid4 { display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(4,1fr); gap:14px; }
.box, .metric { background:#fff; border:1px solid var(--line); padding:16px; }
.metric b { display:block; color:var(--green); font:700 12px Arial,sans-serif; text-transform:uppercase; margin-bottom:5px; }
.note { background:#fff; border-left:6px solid var(--gold); padding:16px 18px; margin-top:18px; font-size:18px; }
.hero { display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:28px; align-items:stretch; }
.heroimg-placeholder { width:100%; height:470px; background:#eee; border:1px solid var(--line); display:flex; align-items:center; justify-content:center; color:var(--muted); font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; }
.kitchen-diagram { background:#fff; border:1px solid var(--line); padding:14px; margin-top:14px; }
.kitchen-diagram svg { width:100%; height:auto; display:block; }
.diagram-label { font:700 14px Arial,sans-serif; fill:#173a2b; }
.diagram-note { font:12px Arial,sans-serif; fill:#70685e; }
table { width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; background:#fff; font:16px Arial,sans-serif; }
th { background:var(--brown); color:white; text-align:left; padding:12px; }
td { border:1px solid var(--line); padding:12px; vertical-align:top; }
.do { border-top:7px solid var(--green-soft); }
.dont { border-top:7px solid #a44f43; }
.footer { margin-top:22px; text-align:center; font:12px Arial,sans-serif; color:var(--muted); }
@media (max-width:1220px) { .page { width:100%; } }
@media (max-width:900px) { .grid2, .hero { grid-template-columns:1fr; } .grid3 { grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; } .grid4 { grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; } }
@media print { body { background:white; } .page { width:auto; min-height:100vh; margin:0; box-shadow:none; border:0; } }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<section class="page">
  <div class="hero">
    <div>
      <h1>Patta Barawari<br>Family Home</h1>
      <div class="subtitle">Architect Brief &amp; Design Direction</div>
      <p>A timeless Himachali family home inspired by Portuguese country estates and English countryside interiors, adapted for Solan climate, family living and low-maintenance ownership.</p>
      <div class="grid4" style="margin-top:22px">
        <div class="metric"><b>Location</b>Patta Barawari, Solan District</div>
        <div class="metric"><b>Built-up area</b>3,500-4,000 sq ft</div>
        <div class="metric"><b>Outdoor living</b>800-1,000 sq ft</div>
        <div class="metric"><b>Budget target</b>Rs 75 lakh - Rs 1 Cr incl. interiors</div>
      </div>
      <div class="note"><b>Design mandate:</b> Build a warm, practical family estate - not a resort, not a glass villa. The traditional Himachali kitchen, modern support kitchen and ground floor family space should be the heart of the home.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="heroimg-placeholder">Reference image (add locally)</div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>1. How The House Will Actually Be Used</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Daily / regular use</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Parents will primarily use the ground floor throughout the year.</li>
        <li>Traditional Himachali kitchen will be the main daily-use space.</li>
        <li>Modern support kitchen will sit adjacent to the traditional kitchen.</li>
        <li>Family dining and baithak area will be used daily.</li>
        <li>Existing family house can continue serving some functions including pooja room and additional accommodation.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Occasional use</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Master bedroom and Zain's bedroom will be on the first floor.</li>
        <li>Guest rooms on the third floor will be used occasionally.</li>
        <li>The full family is expected to use the house for approximately 60 days per year.</li>
        <li>Priority: practicality, durability and ease of maintenance.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>2. Project Vision</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Core idea</h3>
      <p>Create a family home that feels warm, elegant and rooted in Himachal, while borrowing the best proportions and softness of Portuguese / European country homes.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Multi-generational family use</li>
        <li>Comfortable for parents</li>
        <li>Beautiful but not flashy</li>
        <li>Easy to maintain when not fully occupied</li>
        <li>Designed to age well over 20-30 years</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Design keywords</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Warm</li>
        <li>Timeless</li>
        <li>Natural light</li>
        <li>Kitchen-centred</li>
        <li>Covered verandahs</li>
        <li>Stone + wood + plaster</li>
        <li>Low maintenance</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="note"><b>One-line brief:</b> A timeless Himachali family home inspired by Portuguese country estates and English countryside interiors, centred around a large traditional Himachali kitchen with chulha, adjacent modern support kitchen, family baithak/dining space, abundant natural light, covered verandahs and long-term practicality.</div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>3. Site Context &amp; Planning</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div>
      <p><b>Site:</b> Family-owned land in Patta Barawari, Solan District, near Tapalori Durga Temple area.</p>
      <p><b>Existing house:</b> The old family house remains on the property and does not need to be demolished. The new house should complement it rather than duplicate every function.</p>
      <h3>Site priorities</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Orient main family spaces toward best light and views</li>
        <li>Create easy access between house, verandah and garden</li>
        <li>Keep landscaping natural and low-maintenance</li>
        <li>Allow parking and simple circulation</li>
        <li>Preserve scope for fruit trees / kitchen garden</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Area direction</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Target</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Built-up area</td><td>3,500-4,000 sq ft</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Garden / outdoor living</td><td>800-1,000 sq ft</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Overall developed experience</td><td>Approx. 4,500-5,000 sq ft</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Budget target</td><td>Rs 75 lakh - Rs 1 Cr incl. interiors</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>4. Exterior Reference Board</h2>
  <div class="note" style="margin-top:0;margin-bottom:18px;">Reference images are stored locally. The architect will receive them separately.</div>
  <div class="grid2" style="margin-top:22px">
    <div class="box do">
      <h3>Use</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Warm plaster walls: cream / off-white / soft beige</li>
        <li>Local stone detailing at plinth and landscape walls</li>
        <li>Sloping roof with deep overhangs</li>
        <li>Covered verandahs and shaded outdoor sitting</li>
        <li>Arches at selected feature points</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box dont">
      <h3>Avoid</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Full glass facades</li>
        <li>Too many roof junctions</li>
        <li>Overly formal mansion look</li>
        <li>High-maintenance exterior timber everywhere</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>5. Windows &amp; Doors</h2>
  <div class="note" style="margin-top:0;margin-bottom:18px;"><b>Principle:</b> Lots of light, not lots of glass.</div>
  <div class="grid2" style="margin-top:20px">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Recommended</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Large framed windows</li>
        <li>French doors opening to verandah/garden</li>
        <li>Deep window reveals</li>
        <li>Dark bronze, walnut or sage green frames</li>
        <li>Operable windows for cross-ventilation</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Limit / avoid</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Continuous glass walls</li>
        <li>Large glass roofs</li>
        <li>Custom panels that are hard to replace locally</li>
        <li>Overly industrial black-frame look</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>6. Interior Mood</h2>
  <div class="box">
    <h3>Interior direction</h3>
    <p>English countryside interiors with Himachali warmth: cream walls, warm timber, linen curtains, traditional lighting, comfortable furniture and family spaces that feel lived-in.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>7. Traditional Himachali Kitchen + Modern Support Kitchen</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div>
      <div class="kitchen-diagram">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 700 360" role="img" aria-label="Traditional Himachali kitchen diagram">
          <rect x="20" y="20" width="660" height="320" rx="14" fill="#f7f0e6" stroke="#ddcfbc" stroke-width="3"/>
          <rect x="55" y="65" width="250" height="95" rx="10" fill="#8a5a32"/>
          <rect x="75" y="85" width="70" height="55" rx="8" fill="#2d2d2d"/>
          <circle cx="110" cy="112" r="18" fill="#e16b2f"/>
          <circle cx="110" cy="112" r="9" fill="#ffc36b"/>
          <rect x="160" y="85" width="120" height="55" rx="8" fill="#5e3a20"/>
          <text x="70" y="190" class="diagram-label">Traditional chulha / cooking platform</text>
          <text x="70" y="215" class="diagram-note">Raised masonry/stone zone with chimney/ventilation</text>
          <rect x="390" y="65" width="230" height="105" rx="10" fill="#b9a58c"/>
          <rect x="420" y="92" width="170" height="50" rx="8" fill="#d8c8b1"/>
          <text x="405" y="200" class="diagram-label">Floor-level dish washing area</text>
          <text x="405" y="225" class="diagram-note">Low-height sitting wash zone for utensils</text>
          <rect x="70" y="260" width="160" height="42" rx="8" fill="#c9b08e"/>
          <text x="80" y="287" class="diagram-label">Utensil storage</text>
          <rect x="270" y="260" width="160" height="42" rx="8" fill="#c9b08e"/>
          <text x="285" y="287" class="diagram-label">Grain store</text>
          <rect x="470" y="260" width="130" height="42" rx="8" fill="#c9b08e"/>
          <text x="485" y="287" class="diagram-label">Pickles</text>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div class="kitchen-diagram">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 700 250" role="img" aria-label="Modern support kitchen diagram">
          <rect x="20" y="20" width="660" height="210" rx="14" fill="#fffaf2" stroke="#ddcfbc" stroke-width="3"/>
          <rect x="55" y="55" width="580" height="55" rx="8" fill="#d8c8b1"/>
          <rect x="80" y="70" width="95" height="25" rx="5" fill="#8a5a32"/>
          <rect x="230" y="65" width="80" height="35" rx="5" fill="#9fb0a2"/>
          <rect x="420" y="65" width="70" height="35" rx="5" fill="#5f4a38"/>
          <rect x="520" y="65" width="75" height="35" rx="5" fill="#6d6d6d"/>
          <text x="70" y="150" class="diagram-label">Linear / L-shaped modern support kitchen</text>
          <text x="70" y="175" class="diagram-note">Counter-height standing sink, appliances and prep counters</text>
          <text x="70" y="200" class="diagram-note">No large central island / standing table blocking movement</text>
        </svg>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Most important area</h3>
      <p>The ground floor kitchen complex should be the emotional centre of the house and the most-used space through the year.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Traditional Himachali kitchen / chulha zone:</b> primary family cooking area with proper chulha provision, traditional cooking platform and ventilation/chimney planning.</li>
        <li><b>Floor-level dish washing area:</b> separate low-height / sitting-on-floor washing zone for utensils, designed the way it is actually used in village homes.</li>
        <li><b>Modern support kitchen:</b> placed immediately adjacent to the traditional kitchen, not far away.</li>
        <li><b>Modern standing washing sink:</b> normal counter-height sink for standing dish washing and daily convenience.</li>
        <li><b>No large modern island/table:</b> avoid a big central standing island in the modern kitchen.</li>
        <li><b>Kitchen storage / pantry:</b> large storage for grains, utensils, pickles, bulk supplies and seasonal items.</li>
        <li><b>Dining + sitting area:</b> large family baithak-style dining/sitting space connected to the kitchen.</li>
        <li><b>Outdoor connection:</b> direct link to verandah, garden and utility/washing area.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="note"><b>Budget rule:</b> If trade-offs are required, prioritize traditional kitchen, chulha zone, modern support kitchen, pantry, floor-level washing zone and family baithak/dining space before formal living areas or decorative features.</div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>8. Flooring &amp; Material Palette</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Flooring direction</h3>
      <p>Premium wood-look porcelain / vitrified tiles in warm oak or walnut tones. Herringbone pattern in key family areas and wide-plank format in bedrooms.</p>
      <p>Visual appearance should match Dubai house flooring, but with tile durability and moisture resistance. Avoid natural timber flooring.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Material palette</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Element</th><th>Direction</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Floors</td><td>Wood-look matte porcelain / vitrified tile</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Walls</td><td>Warm ivory, cream, soft beige</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Windows</td><td>Dark bronze, walnut or sage green frames</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Stone</td><td>Local Himachal stone accents</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Doors</td><td>Traditional panelled wood appearance</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="note"><b>Flooring principle:</b> The flooring should look like warm timber, not standard glossy tile. Use high-end matte wood-look porcelain/vitrified tiles with realistic grain and texture.</div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>9. Floor-by-Floor Space Program</h2>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Floor</th><th>Spaces Required</th><th>Design Priority</th></tr>
    <tr>
      <td><b>Ground Floor</b></td>
      <td>Traditional Himachali kitchen with chulha, modern support kitchen, floor-level dish-washing area, kitchen storage/pantry, dining + baithak-style sitting area, washroom and bath area, washing/utility area, verandah and garden connection.</td>
      <td>Kitchen-centric family floor; most important everyday-use zone for parents and family gatherings.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><b>First Floor</b></td>
      <td>Master bedroom with dressing and bathroom, Zain bedroom with attached bathroom. Family seating/living area, balcony and washing/laundry area.</td>
      <td>Comfort, privacy, views and family sitting.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><b>Third Floor</b></td>
      <td>Two guest bedrooms with attached bathrooms. Large terrace instead of a living room.</td>
      <td>Guest accommodation and terrace experience.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><b>Outdoor</b></td>
      <td>Garden, verandah seating, outdoor dining, fruit trees and kitchen garden.</td>
      <td>Usable, low-maintenance outdoor living.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>10. Garden &amp; Outdoor Living</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Target</h3>
      <p>800-1,000 sq ft usable outdoor living area connected to the kitchen, dining and verandah.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Small lawn</li>
        <li>Outdoor dining</li>
        <li>Covered verandah</li>
        <li>Fruit trees</li>
        <li>Kitchen garden</li>
        <li>Low-maintenance native planting</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Avoid</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Large formal lawns needing constant care</li>
        <li>Water features</li>
        <li>Plants needing daily maintenance</li>
        <li>Over-designed resort landscaping</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>11. What To Avoid</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box dont">
      <h3>Avoid designing</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Excessive glazing</li>
        <li>Double-height glass walls</li>
        <li>Large glass roofs and skylights</li>
        <li>Resort-style architecture</li>
        <li>Complex roof intersections</li>
        <li>High-maintenance exterior detailing</li>
        <li>Imported custom facade systems</li>
        <li>Overly modern designs disconnected from Himachal climate</li>
        <li>Spaces that look impressive but remain unused most of the year</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Architect note</h3>
      <p>The goal is a timeless family home that will be comfortable and practical for the next 30-40 years. Design decisions should prioritize usability, durability and ease of maintenance over visual drama.</p>
      <p><b>Guiding principle:</b> Lots of light, not lots of glass.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>12. Maintenance Philosophy</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Design for long-term ownership</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Durable finishes</li>
        <li>Easy cleaning</li>
        <li>Weather-resistant construction</li>
        <li>Simple roof drainage</li>
        <li>Materials available locally for repairs</li>
        <li>Low-maintenance landscaping</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Special attention</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Waterproofing of roof and balconies</li>
        <li>Gutter access for cleaning</li>
        <li>Window seal quality</li>
        <li>Ventilation when house is closed</li>
        <li>Water storage and pressure pump planning</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>13. Budget Guidance</h2>
  <p><b>Target project budget:</b> Rs 75 lakh - Rs 1.0 crore including interiors.</p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Priority Spend</th><th>Reason</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Traditional + modern kitchen and pantry</td><td>Heart of the home and most used family area</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Windows and doors</td><td>Defines light, views and character</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Flooring and materials</td><td>Creates timeless interior feel</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Bathrooms</td><td>Long-term comfort and durability</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Verandahs and garden</td><td>High enjoyment value for family gatherings</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="note"><b>Lower priority:</b> decorative ceilings throughout, excessive glazing, complex roofs, oversized rooms and luxury features with high maintenance requirements.</div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>14. Architect Deliverables Required</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Concept stage</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Site plan</li>
        <li>Floor plans</li>
        <li>2-3 elevation options</li>
        <li>Basic 3D exterior views</li>
        <li>Material palette</li>
        <li>Initial cost direction</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Detailed stage</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Structural coordination</li>
        <li>Window and door schedule</li>
        <li>Electrical and plumbing layout</li>
        <li>Kitchen and bathroom layout</li>
        <li>BOQ estimate</li>
        <li>Landscape concept</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="footer">Prepared for architect discussion - Patta Barawari Family Home</div>
</section>

</body>
</html>
